PROJECT¶

This project consist in analyzing Data Science job posts data. Therefore, first involve a Web Scraping process, which script can be find here, in order to get the data from timesjobs.com and flexjobs.com. The former is a normal platform from India and the latter is a platform from the United States of America oriented to remote jobs.

From flexjob we couldn't get the full job description so we worked mainly with their titles and from timesjobs we worked mainly with the job descriptions.

In this script we look for frequency distributions in job features and, keywords and clustering from job titles in description.

In [10]:
def text_normalizer_string(data, language:str='english'):

    """
    The objective of this function is to normalize text data. Therefore, it takes as inputs:
        
        - a string that must be specified in the input 'data',
        - and the language, in the input 'language', in which the articles were written, which by default is english.
    """
        
    import re
    import nltk
    import unidecode
    
    assert type(language) == str, "The 'language' must be a string"
        
    nltk.download('stopwords', quiet=True) # downloading stopwords
    stopword_list = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words(language) 
    urlRegex = re.compile('http\S+')

    def conti_rep_char(str1):
        tchr = str1.group(0)
        if len(tchr) > 1:
          return tchr[0:1]
         
    def check_unique_char(rep, sent_text): # regex to keep only words and numbers
          convert = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9\s]',rep,sent_text)
          return convert
    
    lista = []
    for dat in data:
                
        dat = ' '.join([word for word in dat.lower().split() if word not in stopword_list]) # lower capital letters and remove stopwords
        dat = check_unique_char(conti_rep_char, dat) # remove special characters
        dat = ' '.join([word for word in dat.split() if not re.match(urlRegex, word)]) # remove URLs
        dat = ' '.join([unidecode.unidecode(word) for word in dat.split()]) # reemplacing diacritical marks 
        lista.append(dat)

    return lista
    
print("Preprocessing Data")
flexjobs['Posted ii'] = flexjobs.Posted.apply(lambda a: re.sub('[^0-9]','',a)) # keeping only digits in the posted date column
flexjobs['Posted ii'] = np.where(flexjobs['Posted ii'] == '', 0, flexjobs['Posted ii'])

flexjobs['Title ii'] = flexjobs.Title.apply(lambda a: a.replace('Data Science','')) # removing 'Data Science' words from job titles
flexjobs['Title iii'] = text_normalizer_string(flexjobs['Title ii']) # normalizing job titles

Job Titles Clustering¶

In [67]:
skills.reset_index(drop=True,inplace=True)
role_props, level_props, area_props = [], [], [] # creating empty lists
# categorizing top 25 words
role = ['engineer','analyst','scientist','technical','developer','staff',
        'consultant','architect']
level = ['senior','manager','director','associate','principal']
area = ['data','software','product','marketing','research','analytics','business',
        'engineering','operations','medical']
for i in np.arange(4,25,5): # iterating over top n words mentioned in job titles
    
    print(f"\n Top {1+i} Words Mentioned in Job Titles")
    n = i
    role_list, level_list, area_list = [], [], []
    dfTemp = skills.loc[:n,:].copy()

    for row in dfTemp.index:
        if dfTemp.loc[row,'word'] in role: role_list.append(dfTemp.loc[row,'frequency']) # storing role words
        elif dfTemp.loc[row,'word'] in level: level_list.append(dfTemp.loc[row,'frequency']) # storing level words
        elif dfTemp.loc[row,'word'] in area: area_list.append(dfTemp.loc[row,'frequency']) # storing area words
        else: pass
    
    # calculating each category proportion
    role_prop, level_prop, area_prop = round(sum(role_list) / dfTemp.frequency.sum()*100,2), round(sum(level_list) / dfTemp.frequency.sum()*100,2), round(sum(area_list) / dfTemp.frequency.sum()*100,2)
    role_props.append(role_prop), level_props.append(level_prop), area_props.append(area_prop)
    print(f"Role Proportion: {role_prop}% \n Level Proportion: {level_prop}% \n Area Proportion: {area_prop}%")

    if n == 24:

        props = pd.DataFrame([role_props,level_props,area_props]).T.rename(columns={
            0:'role',1:'level',2:'area'})
        props.index = np.arange(5,26,5)
        
        plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
        plt.plot(props.role, label = "Role", linewidth=3)
        plt.plot(props.level, label = "Level", linewidth=3)
        plt.plot(props.area, label = "Area", linewidth=3)
        plt.legend(loc=0)
        plt.ylabel("Proportion",fontsize=12.5)
        plt.xlabel("Top n",fontsize=12.5)
        plt.title("Categories Evolution",fontsize=15)
        plt.show()

Job Descriptions Unigrams and Bigrams Frequency¶

In [87]:
def top_ngrams(corpus, ngram_val:int=1, limit:int=5):

    """
    The objective of this function is to return the top n-grams. Therefore, it takes as inputs:

    - the data to process in the input 'corpus',
    - the degree of n-grams, which specify if we want bigrams, trigrams or else, in the input 'ngram_val',
    - and the number of top n-grams that we want, which is specified in the input 'limit'. 
    """
    
    import nltk
    from operator import itemgetter
    import warnings
    warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

    assert type(ngram_val) == int, "The 'ngram_val' input must be an integer"
    assert type(limit) == int, "The 'limit' input must be an integer"

    def compute_ngrams(sequence, n): # compute n-grams based on an input list of tokens (sequence) and the degree of n-grams (n)
        return list(zip(*(sequence[index:] for index in range(n))))

    nltk.download('punkt', quiet=True)

    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(corpus) # tokenize data
    ngrams = compute_ngrams(tokens, ngram_val) 
    ngrams_freq_dist = nltk.FreqDist(ngrams) # create a counter of all n-grams based on their frequency
    sorted_ngrams_fd = sorted(ngrams_freq_dist.items(), key=itemgetter(1), reverse=True)
    sorted_ngrams = sorted_ngrams_fd[0:limit]
    sorted_ngrams = [(' '.join(text), freq) for text, freq in sorted_ngrams]
    return sorted_ngrams

def text_normalizer_column(data_df, column, language='english'):
        
    import re
    import nltk
    import unidecode
    import pandas as pd
    
    nltk.download('stopwords', quiet=True)
    stopword_list = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words(language)
    
    def conti_rep_char(str1):
        tchr = str1.group(0)
        if len(tchr) > 1:
          return tchr[0:1]
         
    def check_unique_char(rep, sent_text):
         convert = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9\s]',rep,sent_text)
         return convert
     
    urlRegex = re.compile('http\S+')
    
    columna = pd.DataFrame(data_df[column].apply(lambda a: ' '.join([word for word in a.lower().split() if word not in stopword_list]))) # eliminacion de stopwords y reemplazo de mayusculas por minusculas
    columna[column] = columna[column].apply(lambda a: check_unique_char(conti_rep_char, a)) # eliminacion de caracteres especiales
    columna[column] = columna[column].apply(lambda a: ' '.join([word for word in a.split() if not re.match(urlRegex, word)])) # eliminacion de sitios web
    columna[column] = columna[column].apply(lambda a: ' '.join([unidecode.unidecode(word) for word in a.split()])) # reemplazo marcas diacriticas

    return columna[column]

timesjobs['desc_norm'] = text_normalizer_column(data_df=timesjobs,column='Description') # normalizing job description
timesjobs['unigrams'] = timesjobs['desc_norm'].apply(lambda a: top_ngrams(corpus=a, ngram_val=1, limit=10)) # extracting top 10 unigrams from job description
timesjobs['bigrams'] = timesjobs['desc_norm'].apply(lambda a: top_ngrams(corpus=a, ngram_val=2, limit=10)) # extracting top 10 bigrams from job description

Job Descriptions Clustering and Unique Cluster Unigrams Wordcloud¶

In [86]:
cv_matrix = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=(1, 2), min_df=10, max_df=0.8, stop_words=stopwords).fit_transform(timesjobs['desc_norm']) # vectorizing data
timesjobs['unigrams_words'] = timesjobs['unigrams'].apply(lambda a: list(zip(*a))[0])

n_clusters = 5  
km = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, max_iter=10000, n_init=50, random_state=42).fit(cv_matrix) # clustering data
timesjobs['kmeans_cluster'] = km.labels_ # create a columns with clusters

clusters = {} # empty dictionary
for i in range(n_clusters): # iterating over clusters
    dfTemp = pd.DataFrame() # empty temporary Pandas dataframe
    for row in timesjobs[timesjobs['kmeans_cluster'] == i].index: # unigrams from each cluster
        dfTemp = dfTemp.append(timesjobs.loc[row,'unigrams']) # storing unigrams in the temporary dataframe
    dfTemp.columns = ['word','frequency'] # naming columns   
    clusters[f"{i}"] = dfTemp.groupby('word').sum().sort_values('frequency',ascending=False)[:n] # storing in the dictionary unigrams frequency
    
singles = {} # empty dictionary
for key in list(clusters.keys()): # iterating over clusters
    rest_keys = [i for i in list(clusters.keys()) if i != key] # clusters that are not the "key" iterator
    lista = [] # empty list
    for k in rest_keys: # iterating over clusters that are not the "key" iterator
        lista.append(clusters[k].index) # storing unigrams
    lista = pd.Series(np.concatenate(lista)).unique()
    single = [i for i in clusters[key].index if i not in lista] # unigrams of the "key" iterator that aren't in the rest of the clusters
    singles[f"{key}"] = single # storing in the dictionary

for i in list(clusters.keys()): # iterating over clusters

    text = ','.join(singles[i]) # joinning in a string unigrams that are only in each cluster
    wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color ='white', # generating wordcloud
                    stopwords = stopwords).generate(text)
    proportion = round(timesjobs[timesjobs['kmeans_cluster'] == int(i)].shape[0] / timesjobs.shape[0]*100,2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    plt.title(f"Cluster {i} Unigrams - Proportion: {proportion}%",fontsize=20)
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()
    print('\n\n\n\n')

By picturing the unigrams that only are in each cluster we can conclude some characteristics from each other.

In the first and smaller cluster we can group posts that asks for potential candidates with knowledge in Azure. In the second cluster we can group posts that asks for potential candidates with Machine Learning and Structured Database (SQL) knowledge. In the third and largest cluster we can group posts that asks for programming knowledge or date engineering related jobs because the "Data Entry" and "Computer Science" bigrams where two of the five most frequent.
